On the basis of the aforementioned data, the following processes (Scheme 2
                        ) were suggested for the adsorption of Fe3+ onto the NCDs-SP-MCC-gels with a 3D network. Fe3+ quench of NCDs-SP-MCC-gels is mainly due to the fact that under acidic conditions, the complexation reaction of protonated amino groups with Fe3+ dominates the adsorption, and the adsorbed Fe3+ is partially reduced to Fe2+
                        [65], which reacts with the O-containing groups of NCDs-SP-MCC-gels. In addition, Fe3+ ions were introduced into the NCDs-SP-MCC-gels, which shortened their distance from the NCDs to within the quench radius, and electron transfer between the excited electrons of the functional groups on the surface of the NCDs and the heavy metal ions as well as non-radiative energy transfer occurred, leading to fluorescence quench [66]. And as a result, the NCDs were made to exhibit a sensitive fluorescence response to Fe3+. Therefore, NCDs-SP-MCC-gels responded to Fe3+ with sensitive fluorescence [67].
